A Republican Strategy to Face Obama’s Re-election
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by reaffirming that election fraud is rarer in the U.S. than the number of people killed by the lightning strike.
Republican lawyers have reported only 300 electoral fraud cases in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of U.S. governments have been proposing new laws that make it more difficult to register or go through the urn.
This phenomenon has gained in importance following the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of suffrage in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the election, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court act is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana’s law in 2008.
The Republican authorities rushed to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states forcing voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency of their state.
In addition, five million new voters did not have such a card in 2012.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to get the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID card.
This is far more than enough.
Students who are regarded as voters who vote increasingly for democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs for elections.
Before 2004, no state had requested proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voices.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states promoted laws that abolished voter registration on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general election helped to register about 10 million citizens.
Because of the measures adopted since 2009, the share of registration of new voters has decreased by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, although they account for only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same goes for the Hispanic people.
The latter represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of the voters, made up only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passing of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The US Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage in part.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the passed laws and see them as a clear goal of influencing the results in the countries that are crucial for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electoral board to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new regulations will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
