Analyzing the Higgs boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson has caused some stir last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model – our best or “least false” explanation of nature and the behavior of matter – but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it’s not completely certain that it’s really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still lacking to be absolutely sure about it.
Still, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being fooled, and let’s look at what it’s about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that prevents two objects from being in the same place at the same time.
It’s not possible to break this rule – and don’t try too hard as you’ll hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that a law of this kind also applies to it: the Paulian exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state," whereby this "state" consists broadly of some of their properties.
On this basis, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens called Fermione, who kindly obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, an evil gang of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which is absolutely amazing by the way), are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
However, it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of exceptional banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bot" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More Stable Field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a bit comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be crushed by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is indeed not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator on its own.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have one mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What can all these researches be "good" for, Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to closely examine any deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stuff some holes of the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has major flaws, as it offers no explanation for gravity (up!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found in CERN.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is none.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who in 1962 himself developed the first continuous-stroke laser (the first ones were pulsed) - has already told us that the laser was considered more of a "laboratory play" in the beginning.
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras worldwide and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life with its committee on “dignified deaths.”
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a tasty lunch, he resigns to let himself be helped with food.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The Courage of Ordinary Death.
“My greatest wish is to cure my diarrhea, as it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
“Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Going back to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the ability of the person to take a step back," he notes.
After all, according to several people who work in palliative care, large events take place in the midst of these regressions.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who take care of them.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and by suffocation.”
But because of the illness, I really got to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t have any wishes in life,” she says before accepting to put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, she expects her son, who is from Italy, to visit her for the last time.
At the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers provides personal care and food intake assistance.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for every 11,700 people.
That’s very little, considering that we’ll all die one day.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Depending on the wishes of the dying person, oral care with brandy or Pepsi is granted.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help families and patients alike," reports care director Nathalie Savard.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, no day is like the other.
Alongside an old man of 93 who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows while pushing in his honor, a young man of 36, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois’ home come from their homes, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e., care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter reach the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in Montreal, are more or less specializing exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that causes several palliative care specialists to face the adoption of a euthanasia and assisted suicide law with concerns.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that all have the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain, without any measures being taken to alleviate her.
I fear that patients will die simply because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients bitterly until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
The chances of Hélène Richard’s survival were already minimal when she discontinued difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist I was going to stop the treatment, she replied that she regretted giving up the fight, she told me.
But she told me I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not fulfilling this wish after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be said clearly that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Society of Domestic Palliative Care in Montreal, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which means either sporadically or permanently sleeping the patient by the time he dies.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated all say the same sentence: “I want to die.”
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be alleviated.”
