With Bitcoin it is possible to pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between the parties involved.
In addition, as so often in these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the conviction that the current monetary system, designed by bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros, etc.) and a secure exchange protocol such as BitTorrent, which allows the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers in the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After reaching a high of $30 ($23) in June 2011, Bitcoin fell to $2 five months later, before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) showed interest in this in a report published in October on virtual currencies.
It describes Bitcoin as “the virtual currency with the greatest success”, “competing with the dollar or euro” and “similar to traditional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance into a video game that you can win or buy through gaming (and sometimes also exchange).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and handled by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the accounting book, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded Bitcoins are present in the public account book distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unambiguous electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay for cheating twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other will remain unlinked as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task will receive 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be shared up to a hundred millionth, which leaves some room for manoeuvre.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and the Bitcoin deposits stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real money payment company and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these deficiencies.
Important actors such as Wikipedia deny donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others such as the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the book and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a “mega-final sale” was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper as a result.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented on dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat specifies, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in rethinking hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontally aligned systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB’s report envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be highly significant in the event of the success of this currency.
