A Constitution with a Breaking Bar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever regarding the Constitutional Declaration, which gives it temporary unrestricted power of attorney, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of its work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has relied on a provisional, multi-modified text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal mess.
This new initiative has only resulted in an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his “autocratic delirium” by “continuing to break his word” and “striking justice.”
Its supporters are assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time forcing the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
For the president, it’s also a way to regain public and democratic legitimacy as protest rages across the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American newspaper Time, Mohammed Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to an overhaul vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain unlimited power", the latter should supposedly come to an end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constitutional assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals did not comply with the request.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away, believing that they were unable to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve decision-making capacity, 11 deputy members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were usually passed unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed at the time of the prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum clock of the constituent assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that “the principles of Sharia are the main source of justice.”
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
The liberals, who see this only as a propaganda strike, respond with “hypocrisy.”
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
They have in particular in mind Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia law.
According to Egypt’s specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because “those who are asked to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
You can see the first signs of a theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also nurtured by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"There is currently no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not ultemas, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He acknowledges, however, that “there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
It refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, note d.
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text passed yesterday is strongly criticized for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue is the power of the army.
In line with the military's wishes, the examination of the defence budget is presented not to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as demanded by the human rights associations.
The latter also share their concerns about the text, which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The fact of blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, there is no longer an article about the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
bowing to the holy places,
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: turning water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on the water, feeding the sea storm and fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries are in Jerusalem.
Believers here commit the Passion or Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The trail starts at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews - the wall of lamentation, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave papers with wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take a trip upstairs
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 AD.
They lie on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
All the others take an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the mountaintop.
Visit Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting ones should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum, not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea Scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean desert are kept, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There, the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the Museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Entry is free and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the memorial to the children, which was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars are sparkling.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Amazingly, the Red Sea also bathes in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathing all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea, with a location of 417 meters below sea level, is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and therefore even carries non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and curative mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm stressed nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets are kept in the old town of Tel Aviv, the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city went the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is held by all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre nowadays hosts evening concerts and operas.
Favourite list for tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is preferable not in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get on by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city to the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is sufficient for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without shed, and food that contains both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice of different dishes with hemp and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls made from pureed beans and peas (falpo), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
There are many well-fed cats who stroll comfortably and unhurtled through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don’t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on 9 February 2011.
‘The Great and the Powerful’ Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the livelihoods of the families left in the home.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every worker to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this regulation only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail sector.
However, in the future, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests should be mandatory for all guest workers.
In doing so, you need to take not only language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be proven for both obtaining and extending work permits.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Excluded from this Act are persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The entire body will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law entered into force in the press: What does it actually mean?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, responding spokespersons of the Migration Authority, are concerned with reducing the number of forced labourers.
“Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers,” said Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems encounter migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who will put him under the pretext of help in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of months without food and documents and will work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
“At home, you are promised the One, and upon arrival you will be cheated, get their passports taken, and not receive the promised wage,” confirms the head of the Central Administration for Labour Migration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't scream, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that they not only do not know the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable elementary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Prohibited Access for Unauthorized Persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that most of our documents are fake and we are not registered, and this results in cases of blackmail.
“They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea,” Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
“Don’t worry about the cost of wrong papers.”
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be fake.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for nothing: every migrant who hoped to be able to spare himself the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates can not be bought simply, both officials and civil rights activists agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time that they will get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Home Office ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in crimes extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning to tighten the gun law for private gun owners.
The authorities are responding to the recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the shooting of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "drawing the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - call on the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very small, said Criminal Justice, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes with the use of the registered weapons were committed over the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using themselves on the black market.
At present, according to the authors, you can find any weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market through several channels.
There are five such major channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who spent ten years in the Ministry of Education and in the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts gun orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,” Baranez said.
On the second channel are illegal weapons, which are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen from both the police’s armoury and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons warehouses.
Many military camps have been subject to explosions.
“There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the absence of weapons,” the former military member said.
According to Baranez, weapons manufacturers are also making a contribution to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not withstand international competition and therefore squander the weapons under hand on the black market, for example in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is its own production, sometimes craftsmanship, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and Government Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on the subject of weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from the army and legal authorities.
“Half of all weapons on the black market came through the debt of those in charge who are involved in their work with weapons,” the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% from thefts in weapons production, and 5% from illegal excavations.
A gun shop sales consultant who doesn’t want to be named assures that guns found in illegal excavations have long since been outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get the supplies in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, for example, a type TT, is purchased via an ensign.
The weapon is issued and handed over through the fence.
“The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros each with two magazines,” he says.
“Of course, the police know everything and therefore, if they can’t comply with the crime detection plan, periodically make control purchases from merchants who offer illegal weapons,” the sales consultant adds.
"Like in the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers usually find out about acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested that I come to Begowaja station, where a person would wait for me to bring me to a certain place, where we could negotiate the price.
I only learned the price of the gun there.
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need a friend who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such a friend, but I don't trust him."
There are dealers in the markets, but there you have to go and meet up with a code like "by Ivan Ivanovich, who tells you that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I'm even coming to a few rings of blows about a friend I trust.
He also gives me the rings because he knows I'm not whipping him.
Newcomers are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military member Viktor Baranez tried himself in the mid-1990s as a buyer of illegal weapons when he wrote an article on the subject.
