In the US, fast-food and supermarket workers strike
One in four U.S. teenagers will be sitting behind Mc Donald's cashier at some point
In recent days, there have been massive protests across the U.S. against low wages in Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald’s, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy’s and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will continue to swell or whether they will soon be out of the air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing nonprofits.
In addition to raising the modest wages of ordinary Walmart and fast-food workers, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of founding unions.
So far, this sector of the economy has hardly been organised as a trade union.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, on what is known as Black Friday, when sales took place in the United States that attracted millions of customers, which sometimes led to handcuffs.
On this day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their work and, along with trade unions and left activists, targeted branches of the chain that target people with low and medium incomes.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in the Walmart stores are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many of the slightly paid Walmart employees only shop at their own workplace.
The prices and range of goods made Walmart one of the largest companies in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods only because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain of difficult working conditions, for example missing forklifts or hand-held scanners.
Participants in the Black Friday protests demanded wage increases and expressed their anger over the fact that the contribution to the company’s health insurance had risen from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 an hour cannot afford this increase, they said.
Researchers at Berkeley University in California have found that if the company raises the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That's about 1.1% more than they're donating for wages now.
If Walmart fully transferred the wage increases to the customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
That would be $12.39 per year compared to today.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that protests only occurred in nine states and did not result in any losses to the company.
Black Friday lasted in his store from 8 a.m. on Thursday to midnight the next day, and during that time Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
All in all, the Walmart cash registers carried out nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company’s spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post that a total of “less than five” Walmart employees were laying down the work and the protest action was merely “another PR trick” of the union organizing the protests.
"Free Cash!"
Protests continued in New York this week, but their target was not Walmart stores (which are undesirable in this progressive city and therefore so far inexistent), but McDonald’s and other low-cost restaurants.
McDonald’s says the company sells billions of portions, and yet you’re not given sick days, and you’re not paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage under federal and New York law is $7.25 an hour.
In fast food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too much, and on average their simple employees in New York get $8.90 an hour.
No one deserves less than her in this expensive city.
How it is possible to get along with so little money in New York is incomprehensible to me.
There was a time when almost a quarter of all U.S. teenagers stood behind the counter at McDonald’s after school, but the teenagers were still living with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw it as the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald’s employees, I constantly meet people who complain that they have to get along with this wage and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a commentary in the Wall Street Journal forum whose author notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you don’t know how to feed them.
Participants of the protests, which began Thursday at 6:30 a.m. in front of McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that cashiers and chefs from fast-food restaurants receive a minimum wage of $15 an hour, which is more than a doubling of the current minimum wage.
They continued to demand the formation of trade unions in the fast-food industry.
The U.S. law forbids corporate management to stand in the way of this goal and to exhort or dismiss union members.
On the other hand, the management does not make it easy for them.
The establishment of trade unions in the fast-food sector is also difficult for objective reasons.
The main reason is the high staff turnover.
Dissatisfied
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The culmination of the protests was a midday meeting in front of McDonald’s in Times Square where some local Democrats spoke, including City Councilman Jumaane Williams, who said, “McDonald’s says it sells billions of portions, and yet you are not granted sick days, and you are not paid for your honest work!”
The protesters were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that “we should support the fast food workers together so that they can receive a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!”
According to the New York Times, this was the biggest action of its kind in the history of the U.S. fast food industry.
However, there were only a few hundred local people, not all of whom are employed in the fast food industry, where tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet to be seen whether the spark of these protests will mobilize entire masses.
“The brain has only been moderately overwhelmed so far.”
The topic of extended reality, popular with fans of modern technologies, has recently been perceived by the lens of special glasses.
Google first presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it was announced that Microsoft had also applied for a corresponding patent.
However, in conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft lab in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a transit station for the company’s scientists.
It excites the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and create virtual open spaces.
Please briefly describe what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, most of humanity has been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens that are sometimes touched.
However, we want to look ahead 5-10 years and foresee the radical changes of this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are an advancement, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What do we expect in the future?
Although Kinect has taken the interaction to a physical level, a lot is still happening on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We are trying to change that, working on real three-dimensional imaging systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary for this to be recognized not only the user, but also his environment.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much easier.
And first of all, we should get rid of these silly virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone around you about your actions and intentions.
Actually, every type of interaction with computers is good, but each one in its particular niche.
For example, in the field of controlling objects in public spaces, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and concise gestures instead of expansive gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed control types, for example gestures and language.
- How so?
- For example, we'd ask you to give me this squeaky box?
They say it and point it out at the same time.
- Normally I just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and cannot do at the time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual rapprochement.
I think we will have to work on developing new types of sensors in the near future, which will allow us to capture people’s reactions more accurately.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
What are your demands based on your work with Xbox Kinect sensors on modern cameras?
Is it lacking in resolution, depth or anything else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
Not only the resolution along the X- and Y-axis, but also along the Z-axis must be taken into account.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The human movements are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are not enough, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our Redmond lab with a controllable processing delay of 1 to 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of man and machine.
For my work I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
Kinect is currently working with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used for calculating the depth of the object.
More cameras may be able to solve the problem.
Or amplify the problem, as more calculations would be needed.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system in which we could play with different camera inclinations to see how this helps us in determining a three-dimensional position.
If I remember correctly, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that glasses have the best prospects in terms of applying the technology of extended reality in everyday life?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in your raised hand on the go, but I think the best option would be a "changing" extended reality, in which we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and that is their strength (only you can see them), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality with glasses prevents you from working together on virtual objects.
Let’s imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark of Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is one problem that critics often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
Your hands don’t feel anything!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that the extended reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection material.
She feels the pressure very well!
However, there are also technologies that are actually geared towards giving the "images in the air" some hand-fastness, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located, creates a feeling that is still as weak as someone pushed over the palms at the moment.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outsmart the brain?
Make it think that it feels what it should feel when it is seeing something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed room believe he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms, and large spheres.
So far, the brain is only moderately overwhelmed, and there are still many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes working in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: For many topics, we are only at the beginning.
