Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killerasteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth inhabitants on board set out to find a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question arises as to how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
I do not think there are many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
“That’s Mars and Venus,” says a researcher at the Astronomical Sternberg Institute, Vladimir Surdin.
However, while conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus, that is, in space.
The researchers first discussed the question of reproduction in space with regard to the flora.
Half a century earlier, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit differed in no way from the earthly species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
It develops into a normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a hold; it has to be able to stand on its feet and start moving," explains the laboratory director of the Institute of Medical Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychew.
Without a solid surface, the chicks overlap wildly.
Ten hours later, the newborn’s instincts completely blew off.
The chicks did not respond to light and loudness.
Four days later, they simply died.
“Twice we let chicks hatch and then set the whole thing up because it’s simply impossible to work with them there,” Vladimir Sychew says of the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, there will only be same-sex species on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already sent fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to continue," notes Vladimir Sychew.
After the landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans can do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was in Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing humanity has is the female organism.
Our gull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the question: Does it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Ultimately, no one answered that question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andrijan Nikolaev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Sawizkaja, who was twice in orbit and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there remains a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts who went well after long flights and had healthy offspring.
“The more, the more dangerous it is even on flights into orbit,” concludes Cosmonaut Waleri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the production of artificial gravity.
The Hydrolabor at the Cosmonaut Preparation Center is a compulsory station during flight preparation.
Here, in a suspended state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
Water represents weightlessness.
Even though adults find water pleasant, it is a strange environment; but infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders were witnessing that life on land escaped from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the mother's abdomen in amniotic fluid for about 9 months, and the fact that then it is easier to get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since only 2 weeks go by from birth until the first swim.
“This is not enough time to forget something,” says baby swimming teacher Marina Aksenowa.
While for a newborn child weightlessness is a much more natural condition, the woman does not do without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles regress enormously quickly and thus also the ability to squeeze the child out decreases.
All right, let's bypass this by birth-initiating aids.
The birth could also take place in a special chamber, for example, to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Waleri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the draught, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a stress suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is fundamental to his life.
“This experiment, which we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled, a completely unadjusted person,” predicts RAN’s head of the Bioethics Commission.
So far, the birth of children in space is only theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when the Earth’s inhabitants embark on their spaceships to become a distant planet that will be home to their space-born offspring.
NKA Chief: Control of the Black System Fails due to Politics
The Czech Republic has good supervisory authorities and adequate laws in relation to public procurement, but it is not applicable.
This is what the Vice President of the Supreme Control Office, Miloslav Kala, said in an interview for Aktuáln.cz.
“A law is never perfect, but it needs to be applied correctly – and I don’t think that’s the case with us,” Kala said.
A similar result appears to be a joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative practical example, he cited the attitude of Prime Minister Petr Necas to the so-called "black system".
Recently, the prime minister said that the ODS would not harass entrepreneurs with controls – so is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply come to the government chairman, and the control office, whose duty now is to check compliance with the law, hinders its activities," Kala notes.
At the meeting of the Control Committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you discussed a joint Czech-German project, in which the laws of both countries regarding public procurement were compared.
What was it about in concrete terms?
This is a parallel test that we started about two years ago.
Put simply, it is a matter of the European legislature defining how public procurement should be handled, which is what national legislation is based on, and finally, the actual practical application.
We have compared all of this, and although the examination is not yet complete, we were able to find extremely interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws in us may be even a little "stricter and more perfect", but the actual application is better in Germany in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to draw up new and more precise rules over and over again, and it is also necessary to look at the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What results for you from this project?
It is precisely such a common control that could help us to stop constantly striving to perfect laws and lower and balance thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Economics means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But lowering thresholds for orders does not guarantee that we will also achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even the case that this is how we only burden the system with excessive “paper stuff,” and those who are looking for gaps in the system have it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
They talk about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech Procurement Act.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority to our NK, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NK is the Federal Court of Auditors, which is similar in structure to ours and also has a college that is only formed slightly differently.
The competencies are also comparable to a certain extent, but Germany is a federal state, i.e. these accounting bodies also exist in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The BRH can only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the regional accounting authorities.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
Nevertheless, in some respects Germany is often referred to as a model, although one certainly cannot say that Germany is better in everything.
Is it because the examiners are better?
That certainly isn’t, but as I said, I don’t like comparisons like that much.
In this regard, it should also be noted that those countries that are an example for us are also struggling with problems.
Otherwise, you wouldn't have any cooperation with our authority, would you?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what significance did the amendment of the Procurement Act have for your authority, do you already feel any impact?
Given that this novel is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an effect on our examinations.
Since our checks take place afterwards, we have to expect a certain delay here.
So far, we are more likely to experience effects in the preparatory phase of future controls - for example, we have introduced the new control tool "Recognition of risks of inefficiencies" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts are reviewed and analyzed - here, of course, the changes will have an effect, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positively, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, there may be the problem that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be complied with.
Already under the previous rules, the persons subject to an examination are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the effect that any non-compliance with the Procurement Act is equivalent to a violation of budgetary discipline.
