Simon Ornest: At our concerts we want to gather positive energy
What do you think is the end of the world in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people like to jump on.
With our band The Tap Tap, we’re more likely to make fun of it and say that we’re the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a national benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
For this purpose, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is projected to end on December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which lies in a time zone of 12 hours ahead of us.
From whom does this idea come?
Originally probably from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
In doing so, we not only want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we once handed this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and key rings against the end of the world, with which people can also support us through their purchase via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, together with other performers, also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world with the title "Weltuntergang fällt aus".
Already today the anthem is very popular on YouTube. Will it also sound on the beneficiary concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem will be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the anthems are broadcast live together in a direct connection from Czech television.
The lyrics of the anthem are by Tomás Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also sings Xindl X with...
How did you come to cooperate with both?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many beneficiary events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the barrier-free educational center Studeo, on which we have been working for six years together with the association Tap in the Jedlica Institute.
The students of the Jedliáka Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the editors, we want to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlicka Institute, a separate building is to be built, in which we will move in with this project.
There are several groups and performers at each concert.
What criteria did you choose?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbian, Illustratosphere perform with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jia Suchi.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar “big events” planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at Prague Spring, and we will also prepare an interesting programme with interesting guests for this concert.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the USA - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nonetheless, it has always worked without problems so far, SA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us that I sometimes wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than we did, we witnessed in Russia that in the East everything is still in its beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not accessible to disabled people, and it is still unusual when someone is in a wheelchair alone in the city center.
It is not even self-evident that you leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways do we need to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we're stuck in...
In addition, however, it should be noted that an improvement of the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
However, it is not customary for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but it’s only when our ranks come from significant athletes, artists, actors, politicians, or lawyers that things will really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a caregiver at the Jedlicka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensive.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, among other things, I founded a music AG together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, La Angelovic, tends to say, this is something out of control (laughs).
But the band has only been known in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and this is not visible to the outside, your own performance does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good editors, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to get it that far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do things differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and only accepted after a long time.
There are few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
Of course, the first impression that the viewer usually has is compassion; that is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full life, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities do something, it is not just a step forward for them, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise in many things and also have to demand a certain discipline.
However, I think this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have to rehearse twice a week, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm for many quickly fades away.
But that’s how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them have been there since the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
There is only one: La Angelovic.
We're an open group. People come and go. You can't stop that.
Anyone who has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
