The movie Argo: When it's worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had kept the patronage over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government – it could not afford to throw the shah overboard as it would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt at hostage liberation only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages evoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them cover up an extravagant story of their true identity - they traveled in disguise with Canadian passports as members of a film staff that allegedly visited locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert on "exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's cooperation.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in professional magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictional production society had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Husar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This alternates the mood levels in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly over spit.
And then there are the scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, in the corridors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable new start to his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor, he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime film No Child's Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller Stadt ohne Gnade (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film, which does not play in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that set this director’s previous films apart from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck, however, also demonstrates this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the initial sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet still conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the wrong film rod on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
With the few, however, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality - which does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a phone call in America, or also the pursuit on the runway, seem somewhat artfully).
The weakness of Argo is its all-too-wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some traction, and it’s a film that you can watch with some interest while guating the design and the 70-year-old thriller style.
But the excitement is hard to arouse.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that has been alive in some way to this day, and as proof of the extent to which the ideas of the omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services are overshadowed.
