The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not only in the mind - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a nearby large company, says: "Well, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes voluntarily to one of these old-style libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a little-needed sleeping town at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest educational rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
To counteract this stupid circumstance, a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictional bridges depicted on the euro notes as pretty brushed reinforced concrete thumbnails.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library had to come here!
Winy Maas from Rotterdam’s architectural firm MVRDV, master of bold beam diagrams and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with a familiar calmness and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around with amazement and shrugging their armpits, the naughty Maas piled up his exquisite gifts to a pyramid and concluded his actionist-backed speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So that is he, my proposal for the Book Mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has been dumped.
It is part of a revitalization project, which includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjoining residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is the faceless small town resort, which up to now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an astonishingly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory in order to make a piece of contemporary architecture richer.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: bookseldorado under cheese bell.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, the true pleasures of space and reading open up when climbing the topography on foot.
The all around glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights speak unequivocally the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and soccer-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
"Normally, the bookshelves are located along the facade, and in the middle there is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and flipped the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: In the center are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and house technology center.
A special joy are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall coverings, sometimes brüstung, sometimes stair railings.
Optics, feel and smell are strangers.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake their heads over the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the Municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm one day.
For many years, the Netherlands has been using a millimetre-thin plastic fleece as its root base in greenhouses and fields.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts one, two seasons, after which it is ripe for blocking waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed into plates four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) discolors into a dark, homogeneous, resilient material, which smells like new cars and like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the nearly 500-metre-long hiking tour, you will be rewarded not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide the atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal energy.
Although the Book Mountain is under a glass tumble, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly inside.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand transverse to the glass facade, serve as shade and capture a large part of the sun’s radiation.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest will be done fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial sceptic from the IT industry, already ventured the way to the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even refers to the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse’s “long overdue soul”.
The reason: For the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
For the time being, this is intended to fill the optical gaps in the not yet fully stocked library - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has gone up.
The shelves are filled up to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a semi-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
“I think thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it is only for ornament.
With this, MVRDV has succeeded in the royal discipline that is called identity foundation in the jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is thus balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
It was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy from a policy managed by the US to a German foreign policy.
To make matters worse, Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
The Germans are between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still tackling their role, but they are on the way to a more “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as that of France or Great Britain.
What does a “normal” foreign policy actually mean from a German point of view?
It also shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests affect attitudes in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
In any case, it matters.
But I wouldn’t want to put too much weight on that either, this isn’t a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I believe there is a great deal of understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the US.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Germany may even have some respect for it.
Because it signals that as an international player it has to be taken seriously and its interests have to be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted in favour of a veto.
Are there disagreements between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly has a lot of understanding of the European position.
But due to the political situation here, of course, the government cannot publicly represent this position.
I believe that the real differences are not as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree on its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would of course be a bit easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not currently the case.
So they cannot be part of a broader line and must instead push things out of their own position.
This is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future, Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that the Germans are aware that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player – does Germany even want to take on a leading role?
Or is it still difficult for Germany to lead?
Germany is not yet used to it, this is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a bigger role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a greater role, a variety of anti-German feelings are released.
This does not make it easy for the Germans.
That’s actually the old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be receptive to a variety of neighbors and opinions, and that’s not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European politics is continuously declining, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else is left?
The Germans will have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, it's uncomfortable to you and makes you much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to address the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
