Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhoids.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human Pappiloma viruses, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabies are among the parasitic STIs.
Who are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and trippers are especially common in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungal), trippers, and human Pappiloma viruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - yet: around 20 percent of HIV new infections account for this group.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among adolescents than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In this country, humane Pappiloma viruses are also common in adolescents.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are reported.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections more than doubled from 1,697 diseases in 2001 to 3,698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been decreasing since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2700 cases.
That’s about a tenth less than the year before.
What are the symptoms of a sexually transmitted disease?
The infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, lower abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
In some cases, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubricating infections and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially with frequently changing sex partners.
When diagnosed early, most STIs can be cured and late consequences can be avoided.
