Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the worst-smelling fish in the world?
Norway’s five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest living standards – not only in Europe, but around the world.
Could the country’s secret of success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty bad-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a bunch of dirty, moist sports clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
One must imagine the nasal smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is salt-sprayed trout, which - depending on how smelly you would like your fish - is fermented in water for up to a year.
When darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, dedicated to this, well, really very captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then flush it down with a glass of Aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk General".
People around us eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
“People like the Aquavit more than the Rakfisk,” says Havard.
The spirit can displace the smell.
I'll taste a few bits.
If you avoid bringing the rakfisk near the nose, it is not bad - like sushi, which has a quite long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, much poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling possibilities yet and fish was soaked in airtight saltwater barrels in autumn.
In the deepest winter, he was then removed after a long fermentation and - undoubtedly with the help of alcohol-stamped senses - consumed.
Even a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and comprehensive health care.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, who was far richer than Norway not too long ago, immigrants flock.
Rakfisk is seen as something important - as an essential, though strictly smelling, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the more expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs a proud 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t make it to the world press often, and most people don’t seem to bother.
Here one still hates to call Anders Breivik by name - that racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it refers only to the "July 22nd incident".
Norwegians find it hard to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Mainly responsible for Norway’s wealth today has been the growth of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries since the early 1970s.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays with ripe rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blond hair and prickly blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Their English is just like most people here flawless.
We're not very insidious, we don't like boasting.
Norway has handled its oil richness very cautiously – a large part of the industry’s revenue is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global economic crisis, when everyone threw money around them that they didn’t even have, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And of course eat rakfisk," she adds with carefree laughter.
I stand in the snow and stand for another dish - from Rakfisk I have enough.
A moose burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat mouths me.
But in the evening, the stink fish is on the menu again.
The hotel where I stay is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best - or perhaps the most challenging - fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates with Rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jäger?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
They clap and laugh.
A man falls off his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But maybe it's the rigorous haze of the whole fish.
Mexico’s Enrique Pena Nieto faces a tough start
As Mexico’s future president Enrique Pena Nieto prepares for his inauguration, Will Grant of the BBC analyzes the challenges ahead of him and the mixed feelings of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is currently particularly poor.
Even on better days, this is an ever-clogged city, but on Monday a steel ring was built that blocks several important traffic routes to the capital and creates chaos on the streets.
The goal, however, was not to disturb commuters on the way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president Enrique Pena Nieto will receive the presidential bond and take over the leadership of the nation.
He is facing a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderons, Mexico has proven itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Prior to joining the U.S. president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country surrounding the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute it to the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built, which are a big improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with its name also hang outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect him to make real and lasting changes," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, the PRI.
In particular, as far as security and the economy are concerned, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations for Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects the allegations of the opposition that the new president lacks substance.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share that view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are crucially urban in nature.
Earlier this year, the military was turned on to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
On a spot near a large garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left behind in the last two years alone.
During the presidency of Governor Pena Nieto, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico – a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics of Pena Nietos believe that he did not adequately address the problem of women’s murders during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government has closed their eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the deserted neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her partner.
“When I arrived at her home, it seemed like her body had been washed,” recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the corpse star had already begun.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is attached next to a cross that bears one single word: justice.
But that is exactly what the family has been denied her so far.
The authorities treated me as if I were a chatterer, a troublemaker, a naughty woman.
They want you to just accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and failures,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential bond on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this issue during his tenure.
“I hope as president he is the way he was as governor,” said Pri Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are the most afraid of that.
Prosecutor's Office Says Bradley Manning Didn't Complain About Abuse
Prosecutor contradicts Bradley Manning's allegations of being abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a rejection of the indictment due to harsh detention conditions
U.S. Army liberator accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The prosecutor’s office on Friday tried to determine that army officer Bradley Manning – accused of revealing the greatest amount of confidential information in U.S. history – missed several occasions to complain about the alleged mistreatment he suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month imprisonment in Quantico, Virginia had no complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a defense request to reject the charges - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard prison time - Manning had said that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as a source of information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein went through the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his imprisonment in Quantico military prison, where he had held from July 2010 to April 2011 under enhanced detention conditions.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein questioned him on the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as “excellent” and the treatment by the institution as a whole as “very professional”.
The forms, so Fein, contained no complaints about abuse, although officials had asked Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
“They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) ‘No problems,’ and that didn’t necessarily mean I didn’t say anything at all,” Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to examine the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to have his observational status downgraded to “prevention of injuries.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status – which is one level at risk of suicide – to his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the observational status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning announced Thursday his arrest and relocation to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Naval Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had become unconscious due to the heat.
Not knowing what happened to him or to the outside world was a burden.
“My world was shrinking on Camp Arafjon, on this cage,” Manning said.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell – at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours – and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion because on the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and the guards could not see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally filed an appeal against Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - for example, he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had a chance to wrap himself in his blanket during this count.
During the interview on Friday, Manning said he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket he could have covered, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night. He had previously tried to show an official that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning told the official he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take his detention experiences into account and drastically reduce his detention rate should he be convicted in his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offences, while other charges that are considered too extreme will be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend. The prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all prisoners detained under the highest security precautions in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, illegitimate publication of intelligence on the Internet, the transmission of national defense information and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he is threatened with a life sentence.
The Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to lack of chances
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants – they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at passport control as perplexity spread within me.
Signs referred to two queues: one for "Mexicans" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure what to go to.
I grew up in central California and have been called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - exactly as my friends in Boston call themselves "Ireans" or my friends in New York "Italians".
Later, I chose "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home there was no need for shortcuts or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I won't let go of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all the issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to stay in Mexico rather than emigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue the war of Mexico against the drug cartels, even though he did not give any details.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s leadership to leave them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
As soon as a U.S. government official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, you hear complaints - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - about how the Americans are pressuring the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma go on the war path.
And yet Mexico’s biggest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is because at one point in our family tree, a person – perhaps a parent or grandparent – was not offered a chance in Mexico and migrated north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not Mexico.
And even though we may now be living the American dream, attending good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight that it is the American dream we live - not the Mexican one.
Our identity may be blurred at times, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, it is not.
This is clearly true of the United States.
Furthermore, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership class do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they wouldn’t have gone.
And then we wouldn’t be trapped behind the silk curtain now – with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans take this badly.
While she is a US citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel like they don’t belong to one country or another.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but not one of them is rooted in you.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to resume their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary “ambassadors” for Mexico, who represent their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well.
That won't happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unjust distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through that alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a resentment for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such hope in the germ.
In the midst of the usual blame, countless buildings have been destroyed, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed – and for the first time rockets have been launched from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But although Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not – Palestinians and Israelis have become part of these turmoils.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems anything but appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the armistice agreed on 21 November continues, the struggles this week have strengthened the hard-hearted on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has been controlling the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed the Israelis back, despite the fact that its group itself has suffered great losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are imprisoned in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders might conclude that they have the time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a reviving regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken sides for Hamas – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Jubilant Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist imprint may face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And especially the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Mursi in Egypt – by far the most populous and most important Arab country – on the southern flank of Israel has changed the region’s balance.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
On the other hand, the brotherhood with Hamas is weakened and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a danger.
The Israeli missile defense system, “Iron Dome”, has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
For at least a while, Israel will be able to sleep more calmly.
In diplomatic terms, the United States firmly maintains its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations in violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers – not least thanks to the barriers that run into the West Bank and thus into the majority of any Palestinian state, which protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared illegal, but are being further expanded.
Netanyahu’s Likud party allyed with an even more militant group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these insidious Palestinians swindle and leave them their own state?
If they actually had control of the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire rockets just like their fellow workers in the Gaza Strip?
No, it is better to keep them behind the wall in check and punish them if they dare to lift their heads.
Maybe the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could make them a stroke.
Even if the Islamists, now in power in Egypt and in other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense bill is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economy.
The fact that the pragmatic President Mursi teamed up with Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
As the rest of the Arab world takes timid steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powder barrel that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push Hamas back in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand its diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside.
The correct answer is that which is represented by the more sensible representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and this newspaper: two states where Israel assigns territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt must now, together with Turkey and Qatar, stop arms deliveries in the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial exchanges and a common Jerusalem.
Outlying Arab nations should also push Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the upcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama must also do his part to get Israel to negotiate.
During his first term he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems that he is also reluctant to participate.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has an essential interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian legislation on uniform cigarette packaging comes into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and cigarette smoke-stricken infants and children.
Apart from the different health warnings and images, from next Saturday, the only difference is between the packs in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small fonts.
This means Australia is introducing the world’s strictest regulations on tobacco packaging.
The Australian government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
The government assumes that studies have shown that people who have not started smoking at 26 are 99% more likely not to start after that.
“You can see from a young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image,” says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a slight impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the legislation would favour the black market trade, resulting in cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the intolerable packaging has increased tremendously since corporations British American Tobacco, Britain’s Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed to challenge the laws two months ago at the Australian Supreme Court.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new inventories.
This is a good deal for us.
According to experts, the catch lies in the popularity of social media with exactly the population to which the plan is aimed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most retailers to stop interpreting cigarettes in stores.
The Australian government has banned Internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Whoever markets tobacco and has only a small area left to promote their products doesn’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a healthcare researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has noticed an increase in experience reports on brands written by “very normal people.”
One has to ask oneself the question: is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that they even record a video for it - or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of marketing, the industry is focused on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations – those countries are complaining to the World Trade Organization about unjust trade restrictions, even though none of the countries are doing larger trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has had talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to prescribe photographic warnings in 2001.
It has now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Harder laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures do not affect me.
I just ignore them.
“You just take a tip and put the box away,” says Victor El Hage when he buys a cigarette box that has a photo printed with a mouth tumour.
Honestly, there’s only one reason I’d quit, and that’s my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the “King of the Pack” tobacco trade in downtown Sydney, says the uniform packaging has made it difficult to refill its shelves.
“It used to take me an hour to sort out one shipment, now I need four,” Yu says.
“The government should have just completely banned cigarettes – then we would have told ourselves okay, that’s it, we’re closing,” he added visibly furiously.
In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored.
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane failed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to think about being bored.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is quite annoying - even if books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts cite boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us – and our children – to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thought cycles, which may boost creativity.
And because most of us nowadays almost constantly stare at one or the other screen, the benefits of being bored no longer benefit us.
Should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah.
And no.
I will come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn’t think so.
“Actually, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
The house walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York, Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After reading research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of “wanting to do a satisfying job but not being able to do it.”
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
With apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is in a “disturbance of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only slowly passing.”
Boredom can almost sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, although these two conditions may be related, bored individuals see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed individuals see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German for example: "The inactive mind: The definition of boredom under the aspect of attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content, others heard it at low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they felt more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, couldn't find a reason for them, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a monotonous activity - "like finding faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored."
In fact, he says, we now know that circling and scrambling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to rush around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a buzzing speaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored easier than others.
To measure these differences, in the 1980s, researchers developed a “Scale of Long-Term Oddness.”
On the scale, there are statements such as “a lot of things I have to do, repeat themselves and are monotonous” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have enough time for everything”.
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida – especially in terms of the need for more and a wider variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teens are a pretty tedious bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents with a pager seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored in school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were out of school.
However, only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn’t know if the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "youth is found to be particularly boring," mainly because children and teens do not have a big impact on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - studies have shown that.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors are investigating the relationship between boredom and creativity, which is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the topic for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you to do something else," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what’s best to do.
If you are bored and you use that energy to play and cook guitar, you will be happy.
But while television can cause feelings of happiness in the short term, these can disappear in the long term.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, it can keep him from being bored, but it hasn’t taught him to entertain himself or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: “Self-control transfers from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
We shouldn’t be too critical of them either.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even away from the constant activity and technology irrigation.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, unceasing desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to shut down and relax.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated, it’s hard to get busy once the noise has stopped.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
