Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only university students today are attacked for their views
It has always been my dream to get a place at the University of Oxford.
Both my father and my older brother had attended that university which I once thought was the greatest stamp of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks after I moved to Worscester College in the late 1980s, where I had planned to study history, I had packed my suitcases again, bringing about the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I had gone because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A. N. Wilson slanderously explained that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason – one that seemed so narrow-minded and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my now deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to current reports, a new generation of moderate-right students is suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and growing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week demanded the same level of equality protection that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College’s Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are “often actively isolated, personally attacked, and declared undesirable” because of their political views.
They demand a place on their college’s Equality Committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Their situation was aggravated by a recently aired documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right," depicting Tories as an eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It featured, among others, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Student Association of the University of Oxford, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and wore silver-coloured suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered “sins for introducing higher tuition fees.”
20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of Nottingham University’s conservative student association, said in a Sunday newspaper: “There is a growing left trend in universities.
People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student in Corpus Christi who initiated the request for greater protection, believes such a climate is "unpleasant." 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of Oxford's conservative student association, says she has observed a growing rejection of moderate-right students among JCR members.
“This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and to members’ well-being,” she says.
During my first weeks in Oxford, I was a member of such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to grant Margaret Thatcher - a former student - an honorary degree due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have scared even Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what would happen in the future.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the ridicule of Tory students, but even participated with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the tutorial’s wood-paneled rooms.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate 18th-century French texts into English, and I had not been prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled into it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite hateful.
"Will Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students giggled.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I suggest they take a few French lessons in your free time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt grumbled at me.
I went back to my room with a hanging head.
That evening, I was sitting alone in college at dinner, when someone lightly tipped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student association.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is as it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
At a local pub, I later tried to adjust.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs. Thatcher on all matters.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A beginner in philosophy, politics, and economics who ironically attended Eton College, considered to be conservative, told me, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverse and dirty.
“How do Tories have sex?” one asked me.
They beat each other, right?
I felt like homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay before me stretched before my mind to a purgatory of contempt and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who was based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also because he had advised Thatcher on foreign policy and written speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for his Marxist-deterministic perspective on history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he told me.
I began commuting between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the forties, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said.
They would never do anything like this, not in my city of dreaming tower peaks.
Even my communist friends always showed impeccable manners.
His wet eyes clouded.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory supporter, had given in to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, where another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Although I secretly broke up in shame, I admitted that my parents had put me under a “brainwash” and called her “old fools.”
The relief only lasted for a short time.
It was my father who punched the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time he wrote two columns per week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my hens gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You can call me a crying cock.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragically, it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
