The most difficult profession in the world: the human work animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health if they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, stony paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others are literally working in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulfurous gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the abyssed paths of stone.
While it’s only 250 meters to the top of the volcano that rises to a height of 2386 meters, the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to ascend at the turtles pace, keeping balance and carefully taking their steps so that they don’t slip and crash.
You know that every step can cost her life, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 eurocents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Arrived at the top, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiresomely heavy baskets three kilometers to the Libra, which a mine company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who has been exploiting the volcanic deposits since 1960 and (never better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for every kilo of sulfur.
This is then sold to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocents), because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (€3.8) for each way," explains Anto, who usually runs three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours, after which it is completely done, but at the end of the day it has 138.000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable reward for such a seemingly inhumane effort, however, is three times what he would earn from field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day for the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason as important as the sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs often and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left the first marks on him, although he covers his face with a mask and special goggles.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
“I’m going to work here for another two years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French,” he promises in more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent but life-punished young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter, or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up every morning at two o’clock, because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he has bought from his own money.
Approximately 400 carriers load the baskets with sulfur on their shoulders on the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur mining to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera, which the guards of this nature park charge together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier.
“This work is for animals and not for humans,” protests Madrusin, a staunch, 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as possible" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even if the sulfur burns the throat and itches the eyes, if the wind suddenly turns and clamps the miners in the thick columns that rise out of the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains of serious diseases ... of course, except the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, knee pain, and blisters on the shoulders that have been deformed by the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik is only able to carry 50 kg at the age of 53.
Every day he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is transported by three trucks via a goat path between the bush to the camp in Tamansari at 18 kilometers distance.
“I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here because the volcano was my whole life,” explains Unainik, opening his mouth wide, missing some teeth.
Of his five children, the elder, aged 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but misery lasts from generation to generation in one of the hardest professions in the world: those who work as human donkeys on Kawah Ijen.
