These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of singles and to delaying marriage and births, the result of which is the reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration to counter the reduction of the population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the barely masked xenophobia blossoms against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore’s ruling party achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs, and immigration policies, Singapore’s example also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small apartments are built.
It also has an impact on the housing market.
The Department of Urban Development has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" and allowed to be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the lifestyle of the single person, and that they discourage the construction companies from building large apartments for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger residential units.
This makes them much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards give developers clearer orientations, which were previously put in the way of obstacles if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, talks with Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they won’t have a big impact.
"People are heavily stressed, the apartments and also the upbringing are expensive, which is why it is pushed out by many," says a young manager.
The children can get others.
“For me, it’s important to have my own money and time,” says another, about twenty-year-old man.
Men and women cite their careers, the stress and the cost of property and upbringing as reasons that they cannot have children.
That’s why Singaporeans have the final say when it comes to having children – the government can still do so much.
The offline Private offline is online private
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "that area of private life where one is entitled to protection from any kind of interference".
What is private for someone under the age of 16?
How is this definition applied to everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when he makes known on the Internet situations that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15, who are often online.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to “something very own” on a personal level and “to the password and the user” when they applied it to the social networks.
“I wouldn’t reveal my deepest secrets in a post,” says 10-year-old Jorge while trying to explain the meaning of “private” in websites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail, and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother is allowed to know them, but not the whole world," he said.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
“I wouldn’t share a photo that isn’t mine, or someone who makes the fool,” he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to post obscene photos, naked people, crimes, or to write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge assures to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Including the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if someone answers me, I just upload them,” he adds.
“The social networks are entertaining, I can quickly talk to relatives in the distance or with friends,” he says.
When asked, he replied that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone recommends him to a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask, he admits not to know 20 of the people he added to his friend list.
“That doesn’t scare me because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
According to the boy, no one gave him any hints or asked him for his address or phone number.
“If someone pushes me or asks me to do it, I’ll just remove him from my user account,” he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unfamiliar with experiences known today as cyberbullying.
A friend of mine was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
According to José, the victim did not close the user account.
“He just did it privately.”
After that, he explains a series of steps to safely configure a user account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if he was unsympathetic to me or if I wanted to wipe him out.
“But I know this is cyberbullying,” he explains.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to orient children and young people, it is necessary to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for searching for information, but with the appearance of these pages, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master’s degree in pedagogy at the University of Yale and author of the work “Digital Natives and Immigrants” shaped these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are they, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
“We are the digital immigrants to teach them while we are still learning,” he says.
He explains that this is a complex topic “because we require them to have a defined criterion about what may be disseminated, published or said, and this at an age where maturity is not sufficient.”
“They should also be picky when it’s most important to them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents what privacy is is to ask them questions that will make them think.
“Telling them not to do it doesn’t work,” he says.
Porras then lists some options: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the internet?
Or, would you like to have a photo of you posted, like the one you posted from a friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission beforehand when you labeled photos of celebrations?
And one more question: do everyone need to know what you’re doing in every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they need to trade online as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
“Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks,” he explains.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, elementary school teacher and educational advisor, comments that it is indispensable for parents to carefully read the guidelines of the social networks.
By understanding all sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, the age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children need to be reminded of the lesson "You should not talk to strangers".
Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the release of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was to be theoretically signed by the seven rulers present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the clausule, but then declared that it would be published on the Peruvian government’s website at some point.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the picture of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The little information circulated among the journalists was received by the press spokesmen of some of the unasured governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document that was disseminated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which evoked discomfort among the hundreds of journalists of various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the presidential office of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the Humala declaration and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit South America-Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite press urgency, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was not published.
On the official website of the ASPA you can be convinced that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems for journalists were available, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of The Hague that resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Pisera, met during the regional meeting, confirming that they would accept the decision of the ICJ, which begins Monday in The Hague, in the process that Lima initiated against Santiago to hear the pleas of both sides.
“We will obey and execute the judgment on the differences we are presently bringing to this international court,” Humala said with his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and will continue to be, a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts,” added Pisera, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
Both presidents confirmed that they would submit to the ICJ after Colombia filed an action against the Bogotá Convention after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
At the summit, the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, of Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner, were present.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after lunchtime in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, which stated that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment amount of $17 billion.
Concerning the decisions taken, he said that countries of unasur “will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we are extending decisions on residence rights.”
He said that measures would be taken to “improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, and measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters.”
With the crisis in Europe, “economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant traits, but should serve to expand our production performance and show our peoples a better future,” added Humala.
“We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America, and especially in rural and border areas ... and thus uniting our countries and opening up new economic forms,” the Peruvian president said in a read-out statement.
Among these projects were five Peruvian ones on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are supposed to provide a better connection to Ecuador, although he did not provide any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its re-establishment in the Union of South American nations," he said.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before beginning his participation in the regional meeting that on Saturday in Mexico, he expected a meeting with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict with respect following a judgment of the IGH called into question by Bogotá.
“Maybe tomorrow I’ll meet with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
"We will review all of these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he said.
“I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectful as possible,” Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the country’s new president, Enrique Peca Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc also met in advance to adopt the action plan for 2013, in which dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region will be strengthened.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is chaired by the regional bloc.
