Today, the Ecuadorian head of state took part in the 6th Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, which ended with a call for greater regional integration to ensure sustainable progress, equality and security.
Cause of death due to AIDS is too late detection today
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed the finding: HIV-positive.
“It was like a bomb hit,” he says about the moment he received the diagnosis that the doctor tried to “weaken” without recognizable success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to find out about it; and this with such dedication that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fighting in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was difficult to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At the time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye “because it led to a dead end.”
AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is also possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people who are unaware of their disease still come to the clinic, who have already done damage to the virus and have exhausted their immune system, and who are the victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the occurrence of the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment on time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said HCG's head of HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, saying that this information had been backed by a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
Andrade Villanueva, a specialist in infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the immune system of individuals at the start of treatment, and that those greater chances, which are not drug-dependent, are up to 50 years at CD counting.
Simply put, the above explanations mean that those who are diagnosed with HIV-positive at the age of 25 can, in this sense, "become 75 without problems as long as they are under control," said this expert.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is an average of 76 years.
Even though mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (Onusida’s annual report), it is still true that since AIDS appeared, 60 percent of patients recorded in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May of this year there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
So why are people still dying of it?
- I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so it is in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we have had no care problems with the drugs. The problem is that the people are in a far advanced state because they do not know their infectious state, i.e. at very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us when they already have a concomitant infection. To influence global mortality, early diagnosis is needed, which is why massive detection tests must be offered to all people who need it."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS Prevention in Jalisco) and also patients such as Fabrizio, who had his test carried out at a private laboratory, agree with this proposal, and this for the only reason that it had made a friend of him who, despite his young age, was already a cancerous person in the AIDS phase.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die and don’t want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, just like everyone else.
“I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person,” adds Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO Jalisco to animate with his testimony those who are scared today as part of the global AIDS day.
The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken care of the case of HIV.
The most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; formerly they were delivered individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among the people at risk for new infections are young people.
“Why do you need it?” is a common question of social workers, orientation staff in schools, pharmacy employees and the health system that young people do not want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be located not only behind the counter, but in dispensers in public toilets of facilities frequently visited by young people.
Promiscuity should not be promoted.
They should not be paid the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González responded to the question of whether preservatives would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality doesn't look like this; it's best to bring the condoms closer to those who are already engaging in sexual activity," he said.
Key data of Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
Nationally, the state ranks fourth in new and accumulated AIDS cases, and thirteenth in terms of HIV.
92% of infections occur via sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people for each registered case who do not know.
After the U.S. Court of Appeal has confirmed a ruling that does not recognize the restructuring of Vitro Group’s liabilities achieved through a trade bankruptcy in Mexico, an ominous precedent is created for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has payment problems.
So one could say that the procedures for the survival of the companies that allow the Mexican laws are not valid in the land of stars and stripes in contravention of international agreements.
In practice, the June 15 recognition of the judgment by judge Harlin Hale at the Bancarrotas Court for the northern district of Texas leads to the Mexican companies being subjected to the seizure of their property beyond the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens the door to the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court for three inconsistencies.
While the judge of the case points out that creditors must be subject to U.S. bankruptcy law, the Fifth Circuit’s New Orleans-based appeals court first says that the main case is the trade bankruptcy dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings for companies with a cross-border profile is not known.
In fact, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created, with the American Law Institute being used as a mediator.
Secondly, the judgment stipulates that without the votes of the companies after recognition of the liabilities in the bankruptcy mass held by Vitro’s branches with their parent company, the necessary majority for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case in which this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities among Group companies have been confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles.
It is also correct that, after deducting the votes of the branches, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who complained against Vitro in the United States courts, i.e. the vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have achieved a majority.
The vote was 45 percent against 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for its difficult situation from 2008 onwards in the context of the major economic crisis in the United States, which gave the country blows.
For this reason, the González Sada family appeals to the same Court of Appeal to ensure that the vote takes place in plenary, i.e. by all the judges, because only three of them voted.
If this is not granted, the Cerciorare appeal will be filed, which requires the review of the proceedings by a higher court, in this case by the Supreme Court of the United States.
The serious thing about this case is that the court left aside a document sent by the government of Mexico under the Figura amicus curiae (Friend of the Court), which describes the proceedings conducted by Vitro under the Trade Bankruptcy Act, and which indicates that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries to comply with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
It is also pointed out that the country has been subject to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules for cases of cross-border insolvency, which guarantee the equality of debtors and creditors.
